Part 1

a. Do you have an account with an online service provider? If so, have you read the Terms of Service
agreement?
Yes i do. I never had read terms of service.

b. What is the data use policy?
The data use policy is a compulsory legal disclosure of how a website operator collects, retains and shares personally identifiable information.

c. What are the privacy settings?
Privacy settings are controls available on many websites and apps to limit who can access your profile and what information visitors can see.

d. What is the security policy?
A security policy is a document that states in writing how a company plans to protect its physical and information technology assets.

e. What are your rights regarding your data? Can you request a copy of your data?
The General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), under Article 15, gives individuals the right to request a copy of any of their personal data
which are being 'processed' by 'controllers'used in any way as well as other relevant information.

f. What can the provider do with the data you upload?
Internet service providers can see everything you do online. They can track things like which websites you visit,
how long you spend on them, the content you watch, the device you're using, and your geographic location.

g. What happens to your data when you close your account?
You'll lose all the data and content in that account, like emails, files, calendars, and photos.
You won't be able to use Google services where you sign in with that account, like Gmail, Drive, Calendar, or Play.

Part2

a. What can you do to safeguard your account and protect your data?
Create strong passwords, don't overshare on social media, use free Wi-Fi with caution,
watch out for links and attachments, check to see if the site is secure, consider additional protection.
